jchrest.lib

Class HistoryTreeMap<Integer,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
      • java.util.TreeMap<Integer,V>
        • jchrest.lib.HistoryTreeMap<Integer,V>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Map<Integer,V>, java.util.NavigableMap<Integer,V>, java.util.SortedMap<Integer,V>

    public class HistoryTreeMap<Integer,V>
extends java.util.TreeMap<Integer,V>
    Should be used to maintain a history of states for classes in the jchrest.architecture package. Despite instances of this class extending TreeMap the only functionality available to modify its entries are those functions that add new entries, i.e.
    • put(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object)
    • putAll(java.util.Map)
    Both of these methods always check to see if the new Map.Entry that will be created does not rewrite history. If they will, a RuntimeException is thrown. The following methods inherited from TreeMap are also unsupported since they will either modify entries in unexpected ways, remove entries or replace the values of entries, i.e. they will rewrite the history of a HistoryTreeMap:
    • Map.merge(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object, java.util.function.BiFunction)
    • TreeMap.pollFirstEntry()
    • TreeMap.pollLastEntry()
    • Map.putIfAbsent(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object) (redundant since the put(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object) and putAll(java.util.Map) functions already provide such functionality)
    • TreeMap.remove(java.lang.Object)
    • Map.remove(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object)
    • TreeMap.replace(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object)
    • TreeMap.replace(java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object, java.lang.Object)
    • TreeMap.replaceAll(java.util.function.BiFunction)
